title: Isolated and alone
author: eleanor
text: on the way to college,  i practice my lines,   no one can know that iâ’m just not fine,    itâ’s hard to bear and no one can see,   the pain i carry round inside of me,    my teachers wonder but they donâ’t say,   instead they watch me,  all through the day,   because of the anguish i bottled away,  not many at school wished for me to stay,    i stood in the corner and watched people go by,   they were happy and laughing whilst i wished to cry,   with the burden of the burning fears,  my relief was published with silent tears,      as i get home,  reminders everywhere,   of my dad and how i just didnâ’t dare,    when his first put my mum in her place,   i was useless but to stare at her face,    how she was strong,  yet cried out of sight,   and i stood back before the one sided fight,    he would move and we would curl up small,   but when mum left that was bad an all,    my little brother moved out of his sight,   but i sat still,  and he dimmed the light,    then the shouting which i tried to ignore,   but made it worse and caused an uproar,    he would ask and i would tell him lies,   protecting mum i thought it wise,    the cuts and bruises hid with sleeves that are long,   if people found out then my life would be gone,     now itâ’s hard to forget the past,   the bruises fade but the pain,  it lasts.  and he doesnâ’t give up,  though heâ’s miles away,   a tear he causes,  at least once a day,    its angers me that he can hurt me so much,   when he doesnâ’t care if heâ’s out of touch,    now my emotions run wild and his face i see,   all his beatings and ravings inside of me,    his messages hurt and his phone calls kill,   yet i canâ’t ditch him,  not at will,    i live with strange people,  that donâ’t want me,   thereâ’s only one option to set me free,    i want to do,  it but people,  who care,   would be beyond upset,  i just donâ’t dare,   inside iâ’m crying,   a part of me is dying,    i dejected and broken,   but iâ’m still hoping .  .  .

title: Deep within your heart
author: jodey
text: the answer to your problems lay deep within your heart,  so take a seat and think a while lets go right back to the start,  you seem to have forgotten yourself or got lost along the way,  and whilst weâ¡â¦re on the subject thereâ¡â¦s something iâ¡â¦d like to say,  you havenâ¡â¦t really changed and you have not lost your mind,   try and think real hard as we go back in time, . . .  you was a happy child and you had a lot of friends,  your school reports weâ¡â¦re perfect it drove me round the bend! your teachers (most) adored you â¡â§what a pleasant childâ¡â¨  miss h.  told mum she favoured you although she was slightly wild! there was once a time when youâ¡â¦d give each task your all,  swimming,  football,  eater egg hunts,  very small rolls in plays at school,  we used to play for hours the games would never stop,  making tents,  peter b.  âƒâº zombies the hole lot  if you could take one day to go back to them times,  a happy reassured confident jamie is the person you would find,  to be honest maybe you was just too nice for your own good,  maybe life disappointed you,  everyone made of stone and you just fickle wood.  i have finally come to accept myself for who i am,   i am not the most confident and i am not my biggest fan,  i find it hard to cope with things i find it hard to heal,  but there comes a time in life when you have to accept how you feel,  i donâ¡â¦t think we are that different i donâ¡â¦t think are problems are so strange.  i think we try too hard to be something weâ¡â¦re not,  we try too hard to change.   the word here is to accept,  accept youâ¡â¦re not that strong,  accept you not the most confident accept you get things wrong,  accept youâ¡â¦re not a socialite and actually quite shy,  stop trying to trick yourself stop asking yourself why,  listen to your heart beat how does it make you feel? you forcing your body to be someone youâ¡â¦re not your world just isnâ¡â¦t real,  the drugs gave you comfort they made you into someone youâ¡â¦re not,  they tuned you into your hero confident loud a big shot,  itâ¡â¦s time to ease up on yourself and accept you are who you are,  your future is awaiting and itâ¡â¦s really not that far,  i donâ¡â¦t think that itâ¡â¦s easy it will be the hardest thing youâ¡â¦ve ever done,  but when you accept yourself the world will to and then bruv you have won.

title: Very special daddy
author: jodey
text: you met mummy in a club one very late night,                                    mummy knew it straight away she had met mister right.  as time passed you was the best of friends you made each other smile,       but then mummy took off and moved to brighton for a little while.  mummy said you went to see her every weekend,                                          she made out that she could live without you but that was just pretend.  she said you treated her like a princess you made her dreams come true,       you made my mummy very happy so she decided to live with you.  you put her in your little red car and you made her come back home,              and you both moved in with nanny no more you was alone.  meanwhile up in the heavens when all this was going on,                               god told me â“itâ’s time to go to earth where you belongâ” he said â“abbie,  your mummy and daddy are ready for you now,                    there waiting to take care of you so pack your stuff and go on downâ” not long after mummy found out she was with child,                                     you was so happy and excited the family went wild.  i couldnâ’t wait to come to earth although i loved it in mummyâ’s tummy; id heard a little rumour that chocolate was quite yummy.  finally i was ready to come out,                                             but i only weighed 7. 12 there was no need for mummy to shout.  after 32hours i finally arrived,                                                                     and gazing back down on me i saw your big proud eyes.  iâ’m almost one and a half now and iâ’m growing big each day,                          iâ’m eating more and pooping more and iâ’ve got much more to say.  sometimes i am a pain,  i make a lot of noise,                                                   i throw my food all over the place and i never tidy away my toys.  sometimes i spit out my porridge and it makes you very grumpy,                    but to be honest daddy sometimes you make it far too lumpy.  \t i like to slam the cupboard doors and i like to make a mess,                            but best of all i like to pull the hairs right off your chest.  iâ’m just letting you know that you make me very glad,                                       to know that you are there for me my very special dad.  you make very happy you pick me up when i fall;                                         you kiss away my tears you take me with you to football.  you make a difference to my life you clean my horrid bum,                                    but most of all you keep us safe love from abbie and her mum.
